column25: In Seattle, the net effect of lot splitting is that we are losing tons of opportunities for the real density we need, and at the same time losing trees and habitat without a satisfactory return in density. Lot splitting inevitably and irretrievably leads to more parking places, more garages, more driveways, less space for people and trees, compared to denser alternatives on the original lot.  It may be a solution for some quite small cities, but it absolutely should not be a blanket approach.  Led by Sightline, I used to think it was "gentle density", but observing the resultant structures and tree loss in North Seattle shows otherwise. Apartment buildings and even townhouses look to me to be win-win in both trees and density compared to lot splitting.  My street is the divider for two levels of zoning, and right now I'm seeing a plan for 15 apartments + preservation of large trees, and another plan for lot splitting with 2 driveways in the parts of the lot with the most trees.  Sounds like a small sample size, but it's just confirmation of observations over a pretty wide chunk of the city.

column29:
Edited my ask to simply passing it out of committee, since a hearing is already scheduled.

Added the following talking points to HB 1433 email:

As a homeowner on a budget with a strong interest in reducing my family's "climate footprint" and saving money through efficiency, having a standardized way to assess energy efficiency & electrification options, recommend upgrades, and access a registry of available contractors, would be most helpful.

As a parent and teacher concerned about the future for the children in my care, having more tools in the green buildings toolkit is both necessary and invaluable.
